[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There are two ways of creating&nbsp; and rendering a virtual world. This is what we call rasterization. This&nbsp; is what most computer games have used for&nbsp;&nbsp; many years now. It is super fast and most of the&nbsp; time, it looks good enough. But only if you feel&nbsp;&nbsp; that you can live a happy life without super high&nbsp; quality reflections and refractions. But not me.'

[00:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Because for that, you need something more. My&nbsp; favorite. Ray tracing. Look at these beauties.&nbsp;&nbsp; This you can not get through rasterization, only&nbsp; through ray tracing, but there is a problem. It&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simulates the path of millions and millions of&nbsp; light rays, which takes super long to compute.&nbsp;&nbsp; Like orders of magnitude longer, sometimes&nbsp; from minutes, to even weeks. Ouch. This one&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a beauty, reflections, refractions, volumetric&nbsp; caustics, oh my. But it took us 3 weeks to render. So, rasterization, fast, limited, ray&nbsp; tracing, a complete solution, but slow.'

[00:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So I guess, choose one right? Well,&nbsp; scientists at NVIDIA has an absolutely&nbsp;&nbsp; insane idea: they said, why not do both? Well, my opinion was before reading this&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'paper — don’t do both because it is impossible&nbsp; to pull off. These two ideas are like oil and&nbsp;&nbsp; water — they don’t mix. You most likely end&nbsp; up with the disadvantages of both. That is,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a limited, but super expensive&nbsp; solution. No thank you! So,&nbsp;&nbsp; did they pull off the impossible?&nbsp; We’ll get to that in a moment. And then, splat happens. I mean,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a paper called Gaussian Splats came out&nbsp; and took the world by storm. What is that? It’s a technique that thinks in terms of little&nbsp; Gaussians, representing a scene like this as a&nbsp;&nbsp; collection of little bumps if you will. And note&nbsp; that these scenes can come from real life. You&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just walk around with your camera, and then, you&nbsp; can play in a digital version of it. And the cool&nbsp;&nbsp; part is that it gets better. It is incredibly&nbsp; fast, easily faster than real time. So far so&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'good. However, here is the problem: mirror-like&nbsp; specular reflections are not great. And many of&nbsp;&nbsp; the beautiful ray tracing effects that you just&nbsp; saw earlier don’t look so good there. It can also&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eat up quite a bit of memory, which is scarce&nbsp; and expensive on graphics hardware these days. But the limitations don’t stop there: it doesn’t&nbsp; support any fancy camera models. For instance,&nbsp;&nbsp; fisheye cameras? Don’t even think about it. Also,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'no camera tricks like rolling shutter. So&nbsp; there is tons of potential in Gaussian splats,&nbsp;&nbsp; but if I think about the fact that we get&nbsp; no refractions, none of the good stuff that&nbsp;&nbsp; we Fellow Scholars love so much. This all&nbsp; ranges from very difficult to impossible.'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But don’t despair, because here comes&nbsp; the impossible, but at the very least,&nbsp;&nbsp; insane idea: let’s do both rasterization&nbsp; and ray tracing at the same time.&nbsp; This research work does it by taking Gaussian&nbsp; Splatting, and adding to it something they&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'call secondary rays. This means that there&nbsp; are finally, rays of light in the system,&nbsp;&nbsp; and they are allowed to bounce around. So,&nbsp; are you thinking what I am thinking? Oh yes,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hold on to your papers Fellow&nbsp; Scholars and look at that! A proper virtual world running&nbsp; in real time, and high-quality&nbsp;&nbsp; reflections. I am absolutely loving this&nbsp; one. And, refractive objects like glass,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also…wow. Now let’s whip out that&nbsp; fisheye camera, and…yes! Finally,&nbsp;&nbsp; this all used to be impossible, and now it&nbsp; is not only here, but it runs in real time.'

[03:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here comes my favorite part: the&nbsp; name of this work. You’ll love&nbsp;&nbsp; this. They call it the 3D Gaussian&nbsp; Unscented Transform. 3D G U T. Yup,&nbsp;&nbsp; but that’s not how we will call it. No&nbsp; sir! We shall call it 3DGUT. Much better!'

[04:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here is a nice little surprise. Do you know&nbsp; what super important AI area likes weird camera&nbsp;&nbsp; models and rolling shutter? Training self-driving&nbsp; cars. Oh yes. And this is going to be super useful&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for that too. But is it really better than&nbsp; previous techniques? Let’s see together. Dear Fellow Scholars, this is Two Minute&nbsp; Papers with Dr. Károly Zsolnai-Fehér.'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, 3DGUT looks amazing, but we are Fellow&nbsp; Scholars here, we want to see the comparisons&nbsp;&nbsp; against previous techniques. Well, turns out,&nbsp; there is one earlier method that can extend&nbsp;&nbsp; Gaussian Splats to fisheye cameras, but…oof. I&nbsp; see lots and lots of artifacts and distortions&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. So do you have the guts to have a&nbsp; look at the new technique? Let’s see…oh&nbsp;&nbsp; my, that is a huge difference. The&nbsp; previous one had trouble especially&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with objects that are closer to the&nbsp; camera, but this new one. Loving it. But the story doesn’t end&nbsp; here. There is so much more&nbsp;&nbsp; below the surface. We are going&nbsp; to look at this too in a moment.'

[05:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here comes the best part: they didn’t&nbsp; just close it down to sell it to us. Nope.&nbsp;&nbsp; All this is available right now for all of&nbsp; us for free. The source code is out there,&nbsp;&nbsp; I’ve put a link in the video description, so&nbsp; I hope you Fellow Scholars have the guts to&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'play with it. Sorry, I promised myself not&nbsp; do it again and I just did. But in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp; some of you already do play with it! This Fellow&nbsp; Scholar says that he trained it to only 30%,&nbsp;&nbsp; and it already looks amazing, even through&nbsp; the compression artifacts from social media.'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, but I hear you asking, wait a&nbsp; minute Károly. What is this beauty?&nbsp;&nbsp; Well, I said that there is more below&nbsp; the surface. I said that because this&nbsp;&nbsp; other work is about light transport that&nbsp; happens within these objects. That is,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subsurface scattering. The art of&nbsp; rendering beautiful translucent objects. Now, you can do this in rasterization, here is&nbsp; a work called Separable Subsurface Scattering,&nbsp;&nbsp; it gives you super fast human skin, marble,&nbsp; milk, you name it. I love working on things&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like this so much. And it is so simple, when&nbsp; we published it, we even implemented a version&nbsp;&nbsp; of it that fits into 4 kilobytes. That is&nbsp; crazy — it fits into a file that is smaller&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than half a second of mp3 music. Much smaller.&nbsp; It is available on my website, the link is in&nbsp;&nbsp; the description. To the best of my knowledge,&nbsp; you can also use it in Unreal Engine as well.'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So this is subsurface scattering, but for&nbsp; rasterization, not for Gaussian Splats. What&nbsp;&nbsp; about that? Well, this amazing new work offers&nbsp; you exactly that. And it gets even better,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it supports relighting too. So you&nbsp; have your object, you add an image,&nbsp;&nbsp; and it imagines what that object would look&nbsp; like in these different environments. Super fun. And if you don’t like what you got,&nbsp; you can even edit these materials,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so you can go from skin to glass to wax.&nbsp; I mean, just think about that. Gaussian&nbsp;&nbsp; Splats are not old at all, it’s about 2&nbsp; years old. And now, through the power of&nbsp;&nbsp; open research and human ingenuity, and&nbsp; a hint of AI, reflections, refractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and translucency is already possible for Gaussian&nbsp; Splats. Yes, now you can get reasonably high&nbsp;&nbsp; quality translucent objects in these virtual&nbsp; worlds too. So, next level computer games and&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'virtual worlds are coming! And self-driving cars&nbsp; can also learn better. I am kind of stunned that&nbsp;&nbsp; almost nobody is talking about these papers.&nbsp; But this is why Two Minute Papers exists.'

